metadata.name: Topographic Playing Card #93
metadata.description:
Topographic Playing Card is an attempt to create a pseudo-japanese fantasy map.
Every line consists of randomly spaced lines to simulate the delicate strokes of a brush,
imitating grassy planes and the whitespace symoolizes a body of water.

The colors are randomly choosen from a fixed list of palettes.

Every card has a small chance of being animated. The card can be flipped to
reveal a CSS pattern serving as the card back and generally points towards your mouse cursor when interacting with it.

metadata.name: Shape Study  #86
metadata.description:
‚ÄúEveryone has their own shape.‚Äù
We meet shapes of all kinds in our life.

Algorithmic randomness generates shapes ever so slightly different yet similar. 
I suppose these are someone‚Äôs collection.

‚ÄúWhy do they need to have so many similar things?‚Äù

Perhaps it‚Äôs their versatility in the pleasure they could bring.
Perhaps they‚Äôre meant for different occasions.
Perhaps some are left to search for their very own shapes.

Seeing this, I realized that when people explore themselves or others, it is also a form of shape study.
With what‚Äôs visible and concrete, explore the unseen and abstract.

However, good shapes only come by chance.
Shapes, in truth, cannot be good or bad in and of themselves. It‚Äôs only when two shapes come together that the meaning thereof arises.
I hope you who decide to pick up this work will find the shapes to your liking.

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: NAZCA #6
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

üëΩ Kim Asendorf

metadata.name: DOM II #177
metadata.description:
Owners of DOM will receive FREE AirDrop!

From Proto-Indo-European *d·πìm (‚Äúhouse, home‚Äù), from root *dem- (‚Äúto build‚Äù).

The humans use of stone in architecture and housing dates back to the dawn of civilisation, where its excellence in material, ecological and aesthetic qualities recalls the original concept of home, intended as a shelter from the external world.
The word Home is more representing of the true meaning of DOM as it is tied to the sense of family, homeland and provenance. The place where the heart is.

As a culmination of my personal generative art journey, the DOM II is a natural sequel and a closer, much deeper & intimate look to ancient cities/ villages architecture and typical stone houses. Inspired by Dalmatia coastal & Herzegovina hinterland but you will hopefully find your own dream home.

Thank You!


Press 's' to save the canvas or ‚Äò2‚Äô (or ‚ÄòH‚Äô) for a HD image resolution PNG.
For printing super hires press '4' (can be slow).

Vanilla 2D p5js without additional libraries.
Created with love for code and generative art. 

@Qotonana
December, 2024.

metadata.name: Remains #215
metadata.description:
This series explores the remnants and imprints of past events; the unintended consequences and marks left behind: The floor of a painter's studio, layered with splatters and spills; the face of a rock, sculpted by the relentless touch of water and ice; the rusty hood of a forsaken car, weathered and chipped under the harsh sun.

The art piece is crafted by an algorithm simulating the effects of abrasion from a consistent yet dynamic process. It links a thousand pairs of points, harmoniously shifting across the canvas, with delicate lines. At each intersection of these lines, color is applied. To produce the final piece, multiple layers of varying colors and intensities are superimposed.

------

Controls:

- [x] Save a PNG

- [1] Set height to 768
- [2] Set height to 1152 
- [3] Set height to 1536 (default)
- [4] Set height to 2304
- [5] Set height to 3072* 
- [6] Set height to 6144*
- [7] Set height to 9216*
- [8] Set height to 11520*

URL parameters:

- &height={HEIGHT} explicitly sets the render height


* images with height over 3000 pixels render without animating, downloads a PNG automatically after rendering

Please note that high resolution outputs will take several minutes or even longer to render. Highest resolutions have only been successfully tested with Safari on a Mac. If you would like to have assistance in creating high resolution outputs, please contact the author. 


-----

metadata.name: fx(mash) #32
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: Emergence #61
metadata.description:
Using different noise techniques this work is an exploration of the emergence of complex and organic structures from seemingly random noise. The resemblance to ferrofluids and organic "cells" leads to interesting and almost hypnotic visual effects that evolve indefinitely.

Black and white is the most common feature but there are 5 more colour palettes possible. The parameters are hand picked and selected randomly from a pool, every drop is unique.

Press,
"s" to save a screenshot in 4k
"p" to switch to black and white
"space" to pause
"left arrow" to step back
"right arrow" to step forward

Original artwork by William Watkins ¬∑ Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Act One #267
metadata.description:
Act One, where the mannequin says ‚Äútake me home and I will dance for you forever‚Äù.

This work is an exploration of using motion capture data to create digital paintings, and a little belated birthday ballet for #fxhashturnsone. 
20% of primary sales are donated to Three.js.
 
Keyboard Controls:
[P] Play / pause the dance. By default the dance is paused after a few seconds to render a painting.
[S] Save the current view (live mode).
[V] Capture a short webm video (live mode).

Mouse Controls (while dancing): 
[left drag] Rotate
[scroll] Zoom
[right drag] Pan
[right click] Save image

Best viewed in a desktop browser. The output may be different from the preview image if your frame rate is low, reducing the size of the browser window can help improve the frame rate.

Made using Three.js, canvas API and WebGL2.
The 3D model is based on https://sketchfab.com/3d-models/mannequin-dances-ballet-a24678a81a6f4b6d8f8ba0eb1a78e58b, using motion capture data from dancedb.eu. 
Test in Chrome v107.0.5304.107 and Safari v16.1.

Created by elsif, 2022.11.

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #172
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.
